The paper presents a planner for manipulating tethered tools using dual-armed robots, which involves generating robot motion sequences to maneuver a tool and its cable while avoiding robot-cable entanglements. This problem falls under the scope of robotics (cs.RO), as it involves planning robot motions. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of simulations and real-world experiments, which suggests a focus on practical implementation and validation, potentially falling under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), and systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper proposes a method for determining optimal slider positions, which could involve machine learning techniques, potentially placing the paper under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
